WEBVTT

00:00.802 --> 00:03.025
Welcome to the James River Church podcast.

00:03.285 --> 00:06.990
You're about to hear another inspirational message from Pastor John Lindell.

00:07.010 --> 00:08.852
Lead pastor at James River Church.

00:09.172 --> 00:13.157
It's our prayer that this message is an encouragement and blessing to your life.

00:14.259 --> 00:23.450
Well, this morning, if you have your Bible signed by you to turn with me to the book of James, where we're in a series on the book that we've entitled, The Essentials.

00:25.393 --> 00:29.778
Because what James' concern is for us is that you and I would have

00:30.338 --> 00:37.167
a vibrant faith, that we would have a faith that has a vitality and a strength to it.

00:38.649 --> 00:44.636
One of the ways we have that is when you and I are doing what the word says to do.

00:46.419 --> 00:56.692
One of the things that diminishes faith and the strength of our faith is when we become selective in our obedience to Christ.

00:56.772 --> 00:58.514
I'll do this, but I'm not going to do that.

00:59.330 --> 01:05.579
So what James does is James wants us to evaluate ourselves.

01:06.460 --> 01:08.843
And he gives us a series of tests by which we can do that.

01:10.165 --> 01:12.368
The first test we saw was the test of trials.

01:12.729 --> 01:18.076
How you and I go through trials has a lot to do with where we're at in terms of our service of God.

01:19.218 --> 01:27.730
And then we looked at temptation and James gives one of the best studies of temptation in all of God's word.

01:28.002 --> 01:30.666
The next test was how you and I respond to the word of God.

01:32.870 --> 01:41.164
Today the test is how you and I approach prejudice and partiality.

01:42.546 --> 01:49.537
So today the title of the message is the sin of prejudice and partiality.

01:51.501 --> 01:54.866
Anyone who has observed American society

01:56.066 --> 02:02.512
knows that we are a society that has been torn apart by racial strife.

02:04.114 --> 02:15.544
And every now and then, something happens that again causes people to rise up and the racial tensions flare.

02:17.146 --> 02:25.714
And I would suggest that in some ways, in the last 10 years, it has become even more pronounced.

02:27.554 --> 02:31.378
So let me just say this at the start of this message.

02:32.659 --> 02:49.515
If anyone feels the urge to label me as woke or as being politically correct in giving a message like this, that would not only be ignorant, it would be untrue.

02:51.597 --> 02:56.562
I would add this, I will never let the threat of a label

02:56.802 --> 02:59.586
Keep me from preaching biblical truth.

03:06.716 --> 03:09.881
In 1996, on the heels of the O.J.

03:10.161 --> 03:24.882
Simpson trial and verdict, racial tensions were flaring, and I did a message back at the old building on race and prejudice.

03:25.954 --> 03:31.502
Toward the end of the message is really one of the most memorable moments in my 35 years at James River.

03:31.823 --> 03:41.518
Toward the end of the message I heard sobbing coming from a part of the auditorium and I couldn't be sure where it was coming from but eventually kind of zeroed in on that.

03:41.538 --> 03:55.058
I walked off the platform and walked toward it and it was an African American man who got out of his seat and hugged me and we hugged one another and he sobbed almost

03:55.170 --> 03:56.311
uncontrollably.

03:58.754 --> 04:13.270
As some of you know, Springfield, Missouri and Southwest Missouri has a very sad history concerning racial prejudice, which explains the lack of diversity in the area.

04:14.912 --> 04:20.018
I don't know what you've ever wondered, but when you look at the area

04:20.258 --> 04:40.709
and you have Kansas City with diversity, and you have St. Louis with diversity, and you have Memphis with diversity, and you have Little Rock with diversity, and you have Tulsa with diversity, and then all of a sudden you come to Southwest Missouri, and it's easily 90 to 95% Caucasian across all of the area.

04:42.872 --> 04:47.559
Anybody who moves here from the outside almost always looks around and says, where's everybody else?

04:47.700 --> 04:49.362
I mean, you just have this sense

04:49.602 --> 04:59.276
that there is a huge vacuum when it comes to diversity.

05:01.420 --> 05:07.248
And I want to suggest to you that that is rooted in the history of this area.

05:09.832 --> 05:19.186
On Friday, April 13, 1906, a white couple told police they were attacked by two masked black men

05:20.226 --> 05:21.528
and that the woman was raped.

05:21.568 --> 05:22.690
This was in Springfield.

05:24.052 --> 05:40.416
Fred Coker, age 21, and Horace Duncan, 20, were accused of the rape and jailed, although their employer, a white man, told police that they were at work at the time of the attack and well beyond that time, meaning these two black men could not have committed the crimes.

05:41.838 --> 05:49.970
Another black man by the name of William Allen, age 25, was also jailed, having been falsely accused of killing a white man.

05:50.658 --> 05:57.125
The man who actually had committed the murder had escaped in the events that I will describe following.

05:58.707 --> 06:15.425
On Saturday evening, or Saturday night, excuse me, before Easter Sunday, a mob of over 1,000 men stormed the jail and the adjoining house of Sheriff Everett Horner.

06:17.067 --> 06:19.730
The city and the county law enforcement turned

06:19.810 --> 06:32.602
a blind eye, causing the pastor of the first congregational church to later say, quote, we might as well have had a jellyfish for a sheriff and a set of ragdolls for police.

06:34.344 --> 06:40.290
The mob took Fred Coker and Horace Duncan to the square and hung them from the light tower.

06:42.071 --> 06:49.138
Unsatisfied, the mob returned to the jail, and since the cell door would not open, they took a sledgehammer

06:49.218 --> 06:55.804
And after two hours of pounding on the cell door, they were able to break the cell door open.

06:57.326 --> 07:05.313
The mob then took William Allen to the square and hung him along with the two other men.

07:06.875 --> 07:19.186
Following the hanging, at about three in the morning, they threw kerosene on all three men, burned their bodies, and then went to church for Easter services.

07:20.898 --> 07:28.649
enterprising businessmen took pictures capturing the still rising smoke and the Easter sight seers.

07:30.431 --> 07:44.490
Many on their way to church are coming from church who stopped to pick up little pieces of cloth as souvenirs from the men's bodies and from the ashes.

07:44.510 --> 07:50.418
While other entrepreneurs sold medals, one read, quote, Easter offering, end quote.

07:52.162 --> 07:58.592
that Easter Sunday afternoon, groups of men gathered on the square and talked of burning the black sections of the city.

08:00.074 --> 08:01.376
It was not an idle threat.

08:02.878 --> 08:20.786
Five years earlier, in Pierce City, Missouri, which is just southwest of Springfield, a lynch mob hung two young black men, shot an elderly man and set fire to all the black houses, incinerating an elderly disabled man

08:20.930 --> 08:22.853
who could not get out of his house in time.

08:24.235 --> 08:33.129
They then broke into the militia headquarters, stole guns, and chased every remaining black person out of Pierce City.

08:33.149 --> 08:48.914
Three years prior to the Springfield incident, in Joplin, Missouri, in 1903, a mob of several thousand white people battered down the wall of the city jail and forcibly removed a 20-year-old black man by the name of Thomas Gilliard,

08:49.282 --> 08:55.992
and lynched him in broad daylight, hanging him from a telephone pole to blocks from the jail.

08:56.994 --> 09:05.727
Although Mr. Gilliard maintained his innocence, local officials and law enforcement failed to use force to repel the mob.

09:05.767 --> 09:10.974
Unsatisfied with the killing of Mr. Gilliard, the mob did the following.

09:11.836 --> 09:18.706
They demanded a local man named Hickory Bill, who was in jail for attacking a black person to

09:18.818 --> 09:23.083
be released, which the city officials promptly did.

09:24.204 --> 09:45.247
The white mob then gathered on Main Street, drove all of the black people from downtown into a segregated black district north of Joplin, and then proceeded to launch an attack on that community by robbing and then burning the homes, and then shooting and stoning any black person they saw.

09:45.267 --> 09:47.730
They even blocked the local fire department

09:47.938 --> 09:49.601
from extinguishing the flames.

09:50.842 --> 09:59.576
The mob then turned to another black district south of the town and found that the black residents had already fled out of fear, so the mob burned their homes too.

10:01.118 --> 10:06.887
It is unknown how many black people were killed in the violence on that day.

10:08.629 --> 10:16.882
In the aftermath of the Springfield lynchings, 18 men were indicted for the murders, but only one man was charged

10:17.250 --> 10:19.013
and he was acquitted.

10:19.033 --> 10:34.216
In 1906, a number of African-American residents living in Springfield was approximately 2,300 people, which was 15% of the city's population.

10:35.698 --> 10:41.026
Among them were doctors, lawyers, business owners, and other educated professionals.

10:42.148 --> 10:46.034
Following the lynching, most of them moved out of Springfield

10:46.306 --> 10:51.471
and the African-American population in Springfield fell to 2%.

10:53.333 --> 11:03.502
Sadly, the result of these despicable injustices is still reflected in the demographics of Southwest Missouri.

11:04.744 --> 11:15.794
Currently, black or African-American is living in Springfield account for 4.5% of the population, and in Joplin, Missouri,

11:16.450 --> 11:23.440
African Americans account for 3.2% of the total population.

11:23.460 --> 11:45.490
Bill McCartney, the former head coach of the Colorado Buffaloes and the founder of Promise Keepers, wrote this, Daniel pleaded with the Lord in prayer and fasting because he understood that Jerusalem would suffer desolation for 70 years for the sins of his generation

11:45.986 --> 11:47.788
and the generations of his forefathers.

11:49.149 --> 12:04.066
Most Americans live in a now only mentality, but the historic cultures of the world represent a radical alternative to this thinking and help us understand the biblical principle of generational sin.

12:05.147 --> 12:09.552
The Chinese, for example, tend to take a long look at their history.

12:09.572 --> 12:15.058
They see their own lives integrally linked to their national ethnic

12:15.202 --> 12:16.864
history spanning millennia.

12:17.726 --> 12:26.178
Not only do we tend to be ignorant of the biblical principle of generational sin involved here, but we also just don't like it.

12:27.300 --> 12:31.065
To our highly individualistic way of thinking, it doesn't seem fair.

12:32.287 --> 12:36.693
But God is not bound by our sense of fairness, and the biblical principle stands.

12:37.675 --> 12:42.642
Less than a century and a half ago, the forefathers of our contemporary black brothers and sisters

12:42.754 --> 12:51.164
were being treated as subhuman animals, property to be chained and whipped, bought and sold by many of our white forefathers.

12:52.546 --> 12:57.472
Have we in the church ever repented of that sin in any significant extent?

12:58.774 --> 12:59.575
No, we have not.

13:00.716 --> 13:08.445
We have stood against a lot of other social evils, but we have not stood against racism and called it what it is, sin.

13:10.188 --> 13:12.210
We've been divided by racism,

13:12.418 --> 13:18.148
staying silent, acting with at best only token resistance.

13:18.168 --> 13:20.993
We should feel conviction deep in our souls for this sin.

13:22.015 --> 13:23.377
The damage is incalculable.

13:24.139 --> 13:25.822
The toll is immeasurable.

13:26.743 --> 13:32.754
We should drop to our knees before God Almighty in repentance.

13:42.466 --> 13:50.817
As we come to James chapter 2, the first 13 verses, the subject is prejudice and partiality.

13:52.339 --> 14:07.698
What James is going to do is he's going to show us that the problem with him is that they clash with God's character, they break God's commands, and they so engulf people's thinking that they forget about God's coming judgment.

14:08.994 --> 14:12.239
I want you to see three things as we look at this passage.

14:12.259 --> 14:16.485
First of all, prejudice and partiality ignore God's character.

14:17.507 --> 14:25.820
The very first thing that James does is he points to God's character in James chapter two and verse one, my brothers show no partiality.

14:26.741 --> 14:32.229
As you hold to the faith in our Lord Jesus Christ, the Lord of glory.

14:33.111 --> 14:35.314
What he's saying essentially is that

14:35.522 --> 14:39.768
prejudice and partiality is inconsistent with our faith.

14:40.969 --> 14:43.152
It's inconsistent with who God is.

14:44.654 --> 14:59.794
When we think of God often, we think of his attributes of holiness, justice, righteousness, love, power, knowledge, sovereignty, grace, mercy, eternality, all of these things we could name.

15:00.738 --> 15:12.363
But there is one attribute of God that we don't often talk about, and yet it is frequently mentioned in Scripture, and that is the attribute of impartiality.

15:14.067 --> 15:21.042
God is absolutely, totally impartial when it comes to dealing with people.

15:21.922 --> 15:33.617
We have a tendency when we look at people to categorize people or to respond to them based on their looks, their job, their social status.

15:35.959 --> 15:42.047
But the fact of the matter is, all of those things are not issues with God.

15:43.289 --> 15:45.191
He is impartial.

15:45.892 --> 15:47.634
When he looks at those things,

15:48.674 --> 15:57.809
It's not that he doesn't care about those things, but those things don't weigh into his evaluation of the person who possesses those things.

15:59.031 --> 15:59.772
He's impartial.

16:00.874 --> 16:10.770
In Deuteronomy chapter 10 for the Lord your God is the God of God and the Lord of Lords, the great mighty and awesome God who is not partial.

16:12.578 --> 16:29.028
is very, very interesting to me that when Moses wants to say that he's the Lord of lords, he's the God of gods, he could name any number of attributes, and yet the one he chooses is God is not partial.

16:30.411 --> 16:34.418
He's not a respecter of persons.

16:34.722 --> 16:39.667
looks at people and evaluates them as they actually are.

16:40.047 --> 16:44.712
Really, only he can do that, but he is not swayed by the external.

16:46.754 --> 16:50.418
God's impartiality can be seen in two areas.

16:50.438 --> 16:53.921
He's impartial when it comes to salvation.

16:55.183 --> 16:57.645
Look at it in Acts chapter 10 and verse 34.

16:57.905 --> 17:02.450
Peter opened his mouth and said, truly understand that God shows no partiality.

17:02.786 --> 17:08.053
But in every nation, anyone who fears him and does what is right is acceptable to him.

17:08.514 --> 17:11.097
God has no favorites.

17:12.960 --> 17:14.582
Whosoever will may come.

17:16.104 --> 17:18.427
The ground at the foot of the cross is level.

17:19.608 --> 17:26.858
Anyone of any color, any ethnicity, any race can come to know Jesus Christ because God is impartial.

17:29.301 --> 17:29.842
Second,

17:30.434 --> 17:32.797
God is not partial when it comes to judgment.

17:33.818 --> 17:41.508
Romans chapter 2 verse 9, there will be tribulation and distress for every human being who does evil, the Jew first and also the Greek.

17:42.048 --> 17:46.574
But glory and honor and peace for everyone who does good, the Jew first and also the Greek.

17:47.395 --> 17:51.260
For God shows no partiality.

17:53.042 --> 17:55.365
It's not going to go easier on Jewish people than it is.

17:55.705 --> 17:59.570
Gentiles is not going to go easier on black people than it is whites.

18:00.578 --> 18:10.871
Colossians chapter 3 verse 25, for the wrongdoer will be paid back for the wrong he is done and there is no partiality.

18:11.232 --> 18:22.386
God is not prejudice, he is not partial, he has no favorites, he estimates and evaluates a person purely on the basis of their heart.

18:23.938 --> 18:33.531
For Samuel chapter 16, for the Lord sees not as man sees, man looks on the outward appearance, but the Lord looks on the heart.

18:33.551 --> 18:35.915
This is how God evaluates people.

18:35.935 --> 18:36.956
This is his character.

18:37.337 --> 18:42.323
And so when Paul says, be imitators of God, that's how you and I are to be.

18:45.528 --> 18:46.990
We're not to look at the external.

18:48.051 --> 18:52.818
And while we can't see a heart, we can hear a heart out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks.

18:53.954 --> 18:55.295
We can't see a heart.

18:55.555 --> 18:58.138
We can watch what a person's actions are.

18:58.819 --> 19:02.142
It tells us where their heart is.

19:04.424 --> 19:05.965
We can't see a person's heart.

19:06.486 --> 19:07.887
We can watch where they put their money.

19:08.828 --> 19:11.470
Because where your treasure is, there will be a heartbeat also.

19:11.851 --> 19:13.973
It tells us something about people.

19:14.353 --> 19:16.055
And not that it is ours to judge.

19:16.115 --> 19:20.419
In fact, God says it's not our place by and large.

19:22.521 --> 19:23.922
Second, I want you to notice,

19:24.322 --> 19:26.985
Prejudice and partiality ignore God's command.

19:28.086 --> 19:31.930
Chapter two, verse one, my brothers show no partiality.

19:31.950 --> 19:32.690
That's a command.

19:34.372 --> 19:43.401
In the new living translation, it says, my dear brothers and sisters, how can you claim to have faith in our glorious Lord Jesus Christ if you favor some people over others?

19:46.284 --> 19:52.050
How can you claim to be a Christian and to have faith in Jesus

19:53.378 --> 19:58.825
if you are partial or prejudice toward people.

20:00.848 --> 20:04.232
It's absolutely inconsistent with Christianity and with faith.

20:05.253 --> 20:06.375
The two don't go together.

20:06.415 --> 20:14.866
The root word for the word partiality in the Greek, it's the thought of judging someone by their face.

20:16.546 --> 20:27.221
It's idea of making a superficial evaluation of a person's worth based on nothing more than what appears on the outside.

20:29.865 --> 20:42.482
And when we judge someone, evaluate someone, determine someone's worth on the basis of skin color, it's not only ignorant, it's damnable.

20:44.642 --> 20:59.467
Human DNA sequences have now been mapped out and genome studies have been done, and we now know that human DNA sequences are more than 99.9% identical across people.

21:01.771 --> 21:08.562
Which means this, there is only one race of people, the human race.

21:15.202 --> 21:20.087
And the difference in genetics between any two people in the world is 0.1%.

21:20.368 --> 21:34.683
Now think about this, when it comes to what we call racial characteristics, that is skin color, facial features, the difference between any people is 0.012%.

21:36.585 --> 21:40.790
In other words, there's not much difference.

21:40.810 --> 21:44.914
We all come from one set of parents.

21:45.698 --> 21:59.364
In Acts 17, verse 26, he made from one man every nation of mankind to live on the face of the earth, having determined a lot of periods and the boundaries of their dwelling place.

22:01.388 --> 22:03.191
Furthermore, let me just say this.

22:03.211 --> 22:05.536
We all have the same color of skin.

22:05.556 --> 22:06.738
It's called melanin.

22:07.522 --> 22:10.687
Some have more, some have less, but it's the same.

22:11.068 --> 22:15.955
So there shouldn't be any racism or animosity toward one another.

22:15.995 --> 22:20.042
We are all from the same family.

22:25.010 --> 22:29.176
And James is saying, partiality or prejudice is inconsistent with Christianity.

22:29.416 --> 22:31.520
Look at this in chapter two, verse eight.

22:32.141 --> 22:35.506
What's happened is you have an usher.

22:36.930 --> 22:43.716
And the usher is seeding people in the church based on their economic status.

22:45.899 --> 22:48.521
There is a wealthy man that comes in.

22:48.581 --> 22:53.966
The poor man is asked to give up his seat, sit on the floor, which sitting on the floor wasn't bad in that date.

22:54.166 --> 22:55.568
Most people sat on the floor.

22:56.989 --> 23:03.615
But he's saying, I'm gonna let somebody of means have the seat instead of somebody who does not have means.

23:04.056 --> 23:06.258
And so if something as subtle,

23:07.554 --> 23:12.840
as that is viewed as sin as we're going to see.

23:13.981 --> 23:32.722
How much more would somebody's actions or intent or treatment of another person based on their race be even more egregious in terms of sin?

23:34.306 --> 23:39.271
If you really fulfill the royal law according to the scriptures, you shall love your neighbors yourself.

23:39.291 --> 23:40.912
If you can do that, you're doing well.

23:41.213 --> 23:42.934
Here's the thing about loving your neighbors yourself.

23:42.974 --> 23:48.400
It's saying that you're going to do for somebody else, and who's your neighbor, whoever's in need?

23:49.381 --> 23:51.142
It's with the Good Samaritan parable, Thomas.

23:52.444 --> 23:53.224
Luke 10.

23:54.686 --> 23:59.310
So if you're going to love somebody like you love yourself, it means you're going to do for them what you do for yourself.

23:59.731 --> 24:01.672
It is such a high standard.

24:01.853 --> 24:03.314
It's almost unimaginable.

24:05.762 --> 24:07.644
But that's what he calls us to.

24:10.448 --> 24:15.415
My question is, how are you doing when it comes to loving your neighbor?

24:17.437 --> 24:19.580
Do you only love them if they look like you?

24:21.503 --> 24:25.488
Do you only love them if they vote like you?

24:25.588 --> 24:28.332
Do you only love them if they agree with you?

24:29.874 --> 24:32.978
Do you only love them if they make you feel comfortable?

24:34.658 --> 24:39.986
Here's the thing about racism and prejudice is kind of two sides of the same coin.

24:42.289 --> 24:46.736
I would suggest to you racism is the loud part, prejudice is the quiet part.

24:50.862 --> 24:53.647
You don't have to say much to be very prejudice.

24:55.429 --> 24:56.291
Just look the other way.

24:56.331 --> 24:58.834
Don't say anything.

25:00.737 --> 25:01.518
Don't reach out.

25:02.961 --> 25:03.922
Don't make an effort.

25:05.058 --> 25:06.881
Don't stand against injustice.

25:10.106 --> 25:19.060
Don't show hospitality to somebody from a different background than you are who looks different than you.

25:21.303 --> 25:28.434
James says this in verse nine, but if you show partiality, prejudice, you are committing sin.

25:33.186 --> 25:36.711
Now this is an important thing for us to think through.

25:39.434 --> 25:56.297
Because I would suggest to you that in this country, I'm not just saying Southwest Missouri, but I think Southwest Missouri is gonna have to work very hard to overcome the history and it's gonna begin with the repentance and people owning our responsibility.

25:56.317 --> 25:58.720
I didn't grow up here, but I'm responsible, I live here.

26:01.885 --> 26:02.866
You may have grown up.

26:03.202 --> 26:07.047
somewhere else, you might have grown up in another country, but you live here, now it's your problem.

26:09.491 --> 26:14.337
We have a responsibility to acknowledge the sins of our forebearers.

26:14.978 --> 26:17.302
We have a responsibility to repent over those sins.

26:17.742 --> 26:32.082
Daniel didn't commit sins, but here he is hundreds of miles away repenting over the sins of his fathers and forefathers and doing it, and God acknowledges that as right, and that is what brings about a change in the situation.

26:35.842 --> 26:43.251
We have a responsibility in how we think about things, and especially how we treat people.

26:45.934 --> 27:03.314
And if we show partiality, we're committing sin, and we are convicted as lawbreakers, literally it's your working sin, you're actually working it, you're actually in the process of working sin, and you have been adjudicated as guilty, it's a legal term.

27:04.706 --> 27:10.753
Verse 10, he goes on to say this, for whoever keeps the whole law that fails in one point has become accountable for all of it.

27:11.834 --> 27:20.904
For he who said, do not commit adultery also said, do not murder, but if you do not commit adultery, but do murder, you become a transgressor of the law.

27:20.944 --> 27:21.765
You say, I don't get it.

27:21.785 --> 27:24.829
Why does breaking one law mean I've broken all of it?

27:26.170 --> 27:28.113
Well, let's just say this for starters.

27:28.854 --> 27:30.976
How many sins does it take to send you to hell?

27:32.578 --> 27:32.818
One.

27:34.530 --> 27:48.196
But in the context of this, what we have to understand is the Bible isn't made up of a bunch of individual commands thought up by different people through the millennia.

27:50.520 --> 27:53.426
The Bible is breathed by the Spirit of God

27:53.986 --> 27:57.132
Men were moved by the Holy Spirit to write it down.

27:57.552 --> 28:03.423
And what we have in the Bible is the counsel of God and the reflection of the will of God.

28:03.743 --> 28:11.858
So if I violate one command, I'm violating God's law, his commands, and his standard, and that makes me guilty.

28:13.986 --> 28:16.189
So God's command is don't show partiality.

28:16.530 --> 28:21.597
And if you do, you have violated this command and you become a transgressor.

28:22.018 --> 28:36.098
And if this is in regard to an usher who sets one person in one place and one person in another place, though they maybe don't even know what's happening, if something like that makes them a lawbreaker.

28:37.940 --> 28:41.906
And the language behind it is so serious, how much more would prejudice?

28:45.058 --> 28:49.964
Number three, I want you to notice this prejudice and partiality, ignore God's coming judgment.

28:51.586 --> 28:54.449
We'll all give an account.

28:54.469 --> 29:00.316
In 2 Corinthians chapter five, in verse 10, we looked at it last week for we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ.

29:00.336 --> 29:01.178
This is believers.

29:03.200 --> 29:09.347
That each one may receive what is due him for the things done well in the body, whether good or bad.

29:09.808 --> 29:14.834
And the one whose eyes burned with fire is gonna evaluate not only what we said,

29:14.978 --> 29:33.738
But what we did, what we joked about, what we made fun of, and also what we thought, our thoughts will be laid bare before the Lord Jesus Christ.

29:36.021 --> 29:44.530
And that ought to be so very sobering to each one of us that it would cause us to be very careful not only what we say, but even what we

29:44.770 --> 29:49.056
think, for as a man thinks in his heart, so is he.

29:51.319 --> 30:02.955
That's why James says in James chapter two and verse 12, so speak and so act as those who are going to be judged under the law of liberty.

30:03.376 --> 30:13.490
It's like as you're speaking, as you're acting, constantly be realizing that you will be judged based on the things you say

30:13.922 --> 30:15.544
and the things you do.

30:18.087 --> 30:23.714
Honestly, if that was our guide, there's a lot of things we would never say.

30:25.576 --> 30:29.221
Or post, or write, or think.

30:32.304 --> 30:38.252
James says this in verse 13, there will be no mercy for those who have not shown mercy to others.

30:39.854 --> 30:40.114
Wow.

30:41.346 --> 30:43.108
Oh, see, he's not talking to non-Christians.

30:43.148 --> 30:44.290
We're talking to Christians here.

30:47.454 --> 31:04.635
So if prejudice and partiality have been a part of how you roll, then you have to realize that there is an accountability that you will have before God that will be severe.

31:09.200 --> 31:10.482
We have to realize that.

31:13.634 --> 31:19.020
If you're merciful, there's evidence of Christ's work in your heart.

31:19.040 --> 31:23.264
If you're careful about what you say, what you think, mercy will triumph over judgment.

31:25.647 --> 31:32.755
Now, in the remaining few moments, what I'd like to do is I'd like to give you a few steps in responding to racism.

31:35.157 --> 31:38.321
Number one, call prejudice what it is.

31:38.801 --> 31:39.422
It's sin.

31:41.244 --> 31:43.026
But if you show partiality,

31:43.298 --> 31:44.980
You are committing sin.

31:45.040 --> 31:47.943
If you show prejudice, you're committing sin.

31:50.606 --> 31:54.951
When a person is prejudice, it's not just a cultural misunderstanding.

31:56.913 --> 31:58.414
It's not just the way you were raised.

32:00.497 --> 32:02.679
It's not just you being funny and joking around.

32:02.719 --> 32:05.702
It's not your personality.

32:06.944 --> 32:07.444
It's sin.

32:09.286 --> 32:12.850
And let's be clear why people have said things about

32:13.154 --> 32:24.873
Latinos and black people in Asians and black people have said things about white people and Latinos and Asians and Asians have said things about black people and Latinos and white people.

32:25.133 --> 32:26.996
Everybody's saying everything about everybody else.

32:28.639 --> 32:38.034
What's so crazy about that is that for most people, whatever color they are, they think that's the best, which makes no sense at all.

32:40.450 --> 32:43.093
And whatever form you have prejudice, it's sin.

32:45.477 --> 32:51.905
Number two, that means we have to repent and turn from racism in our past or in our present.

32:52.346 --> 32:54.008
Isn't that how we handle all sin?

32:57.192 --> 33:04.722
And not only should we repent from our own personal sin, but there should be something inside us that calls out for the sin of the nation

33:05.250 --> 33:10.675
just as we would in the case of any sin that has been committed on a wholesale basis in our country.

33:12.917 --> 33:28.553
Much of what we're living with today and the way of problems in our nation's cities can be directly attributable to God's judgment on a nation that for decades has been incredibly prejudice.

33:32.376 --> 33:34.258
I know people don't

33:34.786 --> 33:35.587
like to hear that.

33:37.730 --> 33:42.196
My thinking is this, and the next thing we're gonna talk about is relationships.

33:42.216 --> 33:47.222
If you just bring that up, reach out to people who don't look like you and build real relationships.

33:47.643 --> 33:53.550
When somebody doesn't think prejudice is that big a deal, here's what it tells me, you have no friends of color if you're white.

33:55.933 --> 34:02.802
Because once you have friends of color, you see things very different because you will know them well enough to know what's happening in their world.

34:07.426 --> 34:23.851
When I think of the different people of color who have stood in this pulpit, without exception, they've all told me what life's like for them.

34:23.871 --> 34:27.016
And for their children, it's very difficult.

34:27.036 --> 34:35.890
You see, a lot of times we're not thinking about the things that people of color have to deal with

34:37.634 --> 34:43.902
especially in a society like ours.

34:46.785 --> 34:53.073
I can tell you this, I have tried many, many times to hire African Americans on our staff.

34:53.093 --> 34:54.014
It's very hard.

34:55.576 --> 35:06.930
The reason why is because of the lack of diversity is certainly one thing, but the second thing is they know what it's gonna be like.

35:08.034 --> 35:12.842
Other friends have told how, you know, they just have to tell their kids.

35:12.882 --> 35:17.049
Listen, and I mean, these are personalities, if I named them, many of them have been in my own pulpit.

35:18.171 --> 35:21.456
We have to tell our kids, make sure you keep your hands out of your pocket, you go in the store, get that hood off.

35:23.159 --> 35:24.942
It's the things white people don't think about.

35:27.225 --> 35:34.898
And I'm just saying that there can be a, you know, prejudice is quiet.

35:38.210 --> 35:43.157
There's some, and for you, you don't like Martin Luther King holiday.

35:43.197 --> 35:44.259
You roll your eyeballs.

35:46.822 --> 35:47.583
I don't agree with that.

35:47.764 --> 36:06.130
Well, listen, for a large segment of our population, that holiday represents the progress that's been made in attaining civil rights that have helped their community.

36:09.058 --> 36:18.214
And I mean, I'm thinking in my own mind, listen, the Bible says we should weep with those who weep, and we should rejoice with those who rejoice.

36:18.655 --> 36:21.039
And if they're rejoicing, I'm rejoicing.

36:21.440 --> 36:23.404
If they're weeping, I'm weeping.

36:26.630 --> 36:27.832
So you get a holiday.

36:28.333 --> 36:29.935
Good grief, that's a good thing, right?

36:29.955 --> 36:31.378
Let's have a holiday, right?

36:31.682 --> 36:32.804
Well, working really hard.

36:32.844 --> 36:33.825
I like a holiday.

36:35.367 --> 36:36.529
You know what I'm saying?

36:36.729 --> 36:41.636
But some of you, it greats on you, and I'm telling you, there's only one reason.

36:44.520 --> 36:51.089
And you have to think this through because racism and prejudice are insidious.

36:51.790 --> 36:54.514
And we could take it with, we could take it with

36:54.946 --> 37:00.972
the Latinos, we can take it, and you know, there's just a lot of things that are there that people don't think about.

37:01.252 --> 37:24.594
There was a study done, and it was done by, I read several studies, I read one by Intuit, I read one by Business Journal, but there was a study that was done of 1.8 million people, and it followed people of different races, so you had the Latinos, you had the African-Americans, you had whites and you had Asians, and if you got a bachelor

37:24.866 --> 37:28.651
degree and you were all doing the same job, what was your pay scale?

37:31.534 --> 37:35.659
A Latino made $20,000 less than a white person.

37:37.922 --> 37:44.069
A black made $10,000 less than a white person and an Asian made $10,000 more than a white person.

37:46.472 --> 37:48.434
And then it went on and it showed how

37:48.674 --> 38:01.688
you know, whether you're in business, the cost of doing business or the number of loans, if you're a black, if you're a black applying for a loan for a business, you'll be turned down 50%, 57% of the time.

38:01.768 --> 38:05.692
If you're white, it'll be about 30% of the time.

38:05.712 --> 38:09.817
I'm just simply saying that some of these things are not right.

38:12.139 --> 38:12.740
It's not right.

38:14.281 --> 38:18.546
And I simply want us as a church, if there's one place to ground ought to be level,

38:19.010 --> 38:21.713
There's one place where everybody ought to be welcome.

38:21.733 --> 38:27.020
If there's one place where we're for everybody, it ought to be the church.

38:27.040 --> 38:28.862
That's what the church should be.

38:29.863 --> 38:37.733
A place where we can all celebrate one another and cheer one another and encourage one another and stand with one another.

38:37.773 --> 38:40.476
And if somebody's hurting, we're hurting it.

38:40.516 --> 38:42.859
If somebody's happy, we're happy.

38:43.980 --> 38:48.946
And the world may be divided, but the church ought to be united.

38:55.650 --> 38:56.391
Thank you for that.

38:56.431 --> 38:57.932
You may be seated for just a moment.

38:58.593 --> 38:59.594
So how do we do this?

38:59.674 --> 39:02.377
So back to the relationship thing.

39:02.857 --> 39:07.362
You see, it's when you're sharing a meal, it's when you're beyond like, hey, how you doing?

39:07.742 --> 39:17.452
You know, all of those things have their place, but it's when you actually begin to get to know one another enough that they feel comfortable sharing their heart.

39:17.492 --> 39:19.955
That's when you're gonna hear what life's like.

39:22.337 --> 39:23.378
And honestly,

39:23.522 --> 39:26.848
That's when you're really going to be able to encourage somebody.

39:26.868 --> 39:29.774
Number four, let's see racism for what it is.

39:30.075 --> 39:32.059
It's an attack at the enemy.

39:32.079 --> 39:33.321
It's an attack at the enemy.

39:33.341 --> 39:35.365
It is so demonic.

39:36.026 --> 39:37.970
What has happened in this country?

39:38.178 --> 39:39.700
It's a demonic problem.

39:40.361 --> 39:42.984
Satan is the sower of racial prejudice.

39:43.004 --> 39:45.467
He's the one who causes people to hate one another.

39:45.767 --> 39:50.333
He's the one who gets us to try to treat one another with prejudice and partiality.

39:50.633 --> 39:51.835
Let's see it for what it is.

39:51.855 --> 39:52.716
Let's call it out.

39:52.736 --> 40:00.565
Let's say this is a demonic problem that the Church of the Living God says, enough is enough, and we're not gonna take it anymore.

40:00.885 --> 40:06.312
We rebuke you, Satan.

40:06.332 --> 40:07.954
And finally ask the Holy Spirit.

40:08.546 --> 40:11.229
to restrain your instincts and emotions.

40:13.151 --> 40:17.556
You know, at the natural, you know, our humanities, our humanity, it's fallen.

40:17.857 --> 40:18.558
It's fleshly.

40:21.221 --> 40:30.431
So that's why you and I have to have the Holy Spirit working in us to redeem us and renew us and to help us.

40:31.773 --> 40:36.178
Do you know Peter, the apostle, had prejudice?

40:37.346 --> 40:38.127
Watch what happens.

40:38.147 --> 40:45.862
The Holy Spirit comes to him, works him over, and it happens in the afternoon, changes his heart.

40:46.703 --> 40:55.299
And he said to them, you yourselves know how unlawful it is for a Jew to associate with or to visit anyone of another nation, but God has shown me.

40:55.660 --> 40:59.327
I should not call any person common or unclean.

40:59.347 --> 41:01.010
God has shown me that's wrong.

41:02.370 --> 41:03.952
And then watch this, watch what happened.

41:03.972 --> 41:14.545
So Peter opened his mouth and he said, truly I understand God shows no partiality, but in every nation, anyone who fears him and does what is right is acceptable to him.

41:14.605 --> 41:19.091
Peter says, I learned that partiality is wrong.

41:19.231 --> 41:20.813
God learned prejudice is wrong.

41:21.213 --> 41:23.196
And the Holy Spirit's the one who showed him.

41:23.236 --> 41:28.122
We all need to pray this prayer.

41:29.003 --> 41:29.504
Here it is.

41:29.784 --> 41:31.346
God, help me to see people.

41:32.898 --> 41:41.691
and the love people like you see people and like you love people.

41:41.731 --> 41:43.734
I want to encourage you, pray that prayer with you.

41:44.636 --> 41:52.688
God, help us to see people and love people like you see people and love people.

41:54.090 --> 41:56.754
God, may we be agents of courage

41:56.866 --> 42:00.109
agents of love, agents of change.

42:00.569 --> 42:08.456
Lord, in this society and where once there was heard in sorrow and pain, may there be healing and life.

42:08.776 --> 42:26.852
Lord, may there be a grace from God and the power of the Holy Spirit that would level the ground at the foot of the cross, that men and women of every race, of every background might come to know you, might come to love you, might come to worship you,

42:26.832 --> 42:29.214
And oh, God, may we be like you.

42:29.415 --> 42:39.705
May we not judge by outward appearances, but Lord, in our heart, may we love each and every person knowing they were made in the image of God.

42:40.085 --> 42:47.773
May we be outraged at prejudice, and Lord, may we work to make things right in the name of Jesus.

42:47.793 --> 42:52.458
Oh, God, may we as a church be mighty and powerful.

42:52.478 --> 42:56.402
May we be sold in life in our generation.

42:56.930 --> 43:02.898
Father, we thank You for it in Jesus' name.

